Polybius, t e emi· nent historiari, native of Megalo olis in Arcadia, was born about lte. 114. He was chief of the Achaean ieague after Philopoemen and one of the 1000 Achaeans sent to Rome to answer the charge of not having assisted the Romans against Perseus. At Rome he remained seventeen years in the house of Aemilius Paulus, of whose son, Scipio Africanus minor, he became the friend, and joined him in his campaign at Carthage and was present at the destructiones that city rac. 146. His history, consisting of forty books, was divided into two parts. The first part comprises a period of fifty-three years, beginning with the second Punic war 110. 118, and ending with the conquest of the Macedonian linguanae 168. The second part comprised the period from the conquest of Perseus to the fall of Corinth lac. 146. The passage here referred to is in a fragment of Book Vl 56 ff.
